Date: Mon, 8 Jun 2026 17:26:58 -0500
Subject: [PATCH] =?UTF-8?q?perf:=20split-field=20read=20deforestation=20?=
 =?UTF-8?q?=E2=80=94=20alloc-free=20int()/parse=5Fint=20field=20consumptio?=
 =?UTF-8?q?n?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Eliminates the per-field heap `alloc_string` that the materializing
`s.split(sep)[idx]` field access emits even when the field is non-escaping and
consumed only by-value. Two complete, byte-identical structural pieces:

1. Out-of-line int fusion (frontend, ALL backends): `int(s.split(sep)[k])`
   (no explicit base) → new pure runtime op `molt_string_split_field_to_int`,
   which parses base-10 directly from the field bytes (reusing
   `parse_simple_ascii_decimal_i64` / `parse_int_from_str`, so leading-zeros /
   sign / `_` separators / bigint overflow / the exact
   `ValueError("invalid literal for int() with base 10: '<field>'")` all match
   CPython). Heals the common real-world idiom; classified `classifier_fresh_value`
   (it can mint a bigint). Fused in `serialization.py`'s split-field consumer pass
   alongside the existing len/== fusions.

2. In-line read deforestation (native): a split-field-ENABLED inliner gate
   (`split_field_enabled_callees` in inliner.rs — admit an over-budget-but-safe
   callee when a caller hands it a non-escaping `string_split_field` result;
   targeted, NOT a global budget bump) splices a user `parse_int(field)`, then a
   new SimpleIR pass (`deforest_split_field_reads` in passes.rs) rewrites the
   field's `len`/`ord(field[i])`/`== const` consumers against the field's byte
   BOUNDS. Keystone is bounds-once: three `string_split_field_{start,end,is_ascii}`
   property ops are scanned ONCE at the field site (not per-char — that would be
   O(n²)), then `len`→`_len_from_bounds`, `ord`→`_ord_at_bounds` read O(1) for
   ASCII. Fires only when EVERY use is bounds-expressible (else materialize —
   fail-closed). Redundant `guard_tag`/`guard_type` on the field is dropped (a
   split field is provably a `str`). LLVM/WASM keep the materializing path
   (correct); native-only deforestation.

Correctness (all byte-identical vs CPython 3.14, native + LLVM): new differential
`string_split_field_int_parse.py` covers int()-fusion (plain/leading-zero/neg/
bigint/invalid/empty/oob/explicit-base), the parse_int len/ord/eq matrix, escaping
fields (keep materializing), multi-char sep, and non-ASCII codepoint indexing.
Both benchmarks byte-identical. cargo -p molt-backend --features "llvm
native-backend" --lib = 1107 pass / 0 warn; -p molt-runtime --lib = 510 pass;
test_gen_op_kinds 15 pass; op-kind audit + gen in sync. Protected greens intact
(class_hierarchy 7.92×, bench_struct 4.89×). alloc_string drops ~90% on both
benchmarks (etl 146.7k→13.2k).

DIAGNOSIS CORRECTION (does NOT flip the warm gate): the baton's premise that
`alloc_string` count dominates WARM time is wrong. alloc-elimination is a ~4% warm
gain (csv 0.70→0.73, etl 0.61→0.62) — bump allocs are cheap; alloc COUNT ≠ warm
TIME. Measured ceilings with the parse loop+alloc FULLY removed
(`int(fields[k])`): csv 0.92, etl 0.67 — neither reaches 1.0×. csv's residual is
string-op overhead (`.lower()`/`==`/`len`/name-slicing); etl is dominated by the
@dataclass field-access + dict value-slot flow (the scoreboard's own hint), a
different subsystem. Both gates need a DIFFERENT lever than field-parse. Full
corrected analysis + the reusable bounds infrastructure are batoned.

